Risk Prediction of Theft from Buildings in Chicago

Chi Zhang (Partner:Zhijie Zhou)

2020/10/23

1. Introduction

According to the analysis of Neighborhoodscout, Chicago is only safer than 7% other cities in the United States. There are total of 115,279 crimes happened in the past year, 316 incidents a day on average. Crimes related with property accounts for 76.2% of the total amount.

In this report, the risk of theft from buildings in Chicago is predicted using a machine learning model. It aims to provide some insights to the policy making of public safety for the future with existed open data, such as the spatial distribution of sanitation complaints, graffiti and liquor retails. The prediction model can be a useful tool for decision making, but some limitations due to the bias of data set cannot be neglected. The accuracy and generalizability of this model are discussed in the end.

3. Data Wrangling

3.1 Crime Data Wrangling

The crimes of theft from buildings in 2018 are wrangled from Chicago Opendata. The number of theft could be lower than the fact for following potential bias.

1)Thefts involving small amounts may not be reported. Since most theft cases are hard to arrest the thief and get the money back and the process of reporting is quite complicated, some people are not willing to report. This also depends on the income level of the victims. Households with higher income are more likely to balance the money and value of time, and then give up doing a report.

2)Besides, some thefts are not detectable. In Chicago, thefts from buildings are majority happened in public places like pubs and restaurants where crowds of people gathered. Unlike robbery, these crimes are hard to detect if the loss of money is small and there is no monitor recordings.

4.2 Nearest neighbor features

Spatial bias can exist in count of factors within each cell. Because it is possible that the total number of factors is small in one cell, while the overall density at a larger scale is relatively high. Considering spatial correlation, nearest neighbor distance is calculated.

# convinience to reduce length of function names.
st_c <- st_coordinates
st_coid <- st_centroid
k_num = 3

# nn_function
nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
  output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
    pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

## create NN from abandoned cars
vars_net <- vars_net %>%
    mutate(Abandoned_Cars.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(abandonCars),
                                           k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Garbage_Carts.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(garbageCarts),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Graffiti.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(graffiti),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Liquor_Retail.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(liquorRetail),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Police_Stations.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(policeStations),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Pot_Holes.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(potHoles),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Rodent_Baiting.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(rodentBaiting),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Sanitation_Complaints.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(sanitationComplaints),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Street_Lights_All_Out.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(stLightsOut),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
  mutate(Tobacco_Retail.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(tobaccoRetail),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
    mutate(Tree_Debris.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(treeDebris),
                                          k = k_num)) %>%
    mutate(Tree_Trim.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)),
                                          st_c(treeTrim),
                                          k = k_num))

4.4 Join Police District and Neighborhood Name to the Final Net

Neighborhood name and police district are spatially joined to the final_net using grid cell centroids. Some cells with NA value at the urban periphery are dropped.

## important to drop the geometry from joining features
final_net <-
  left_join(crime_net, st_drop_geometry(vars_net), by="uniqueID") 

final_net <-
  st_centroid(final_net) %>%
    st_join(dplyr::select(neighborhoods, name), by = "uniqueID") %>%
    st_join(dplyr::select(policeDistricts, District), by = "uniqueID") %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(dplyr::select(final_net, geometry, uniqueID)) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
  na.omit()

dplyr::select(final_net, name, District) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = Value)) +
  facet_wrap(~Variable) +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, option = "C") +
  labs(title = "Aggregate Areas") +
  mapTheme() + theme(legend.position = "none")

4.5 Exploring the Spatial Process of Theft from Buildings

Local Morans I is calculated considering spatial autocorrelation of the crimes. A hotspot map illustrates urban areas where the p-value is less than 0.05, which means the possibility of theft from buildings in these area is significantly high. It is a very important feature to raise the accuracy and generalizability of prediction in hotspot areas.

## generates warnings from PROJ issues
## {spdep} to make polygon to neighborhoods... 
final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)
## ... and neighborhoods to list of weights
final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

## see localmoran
local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$countTheftBldg18, final_net.weights) %>%
  as.data.frame()

# join local Moran's I results to fishnet

5. Regression Analysis

5.1 Distribution of the Dependent Variable

Before regression analysis, a histogram is plotted to show the distribution of theft from buildings by grid cell. Its clear that the distribution is left-skewed with majority of crimes near to zero. Given the distribution pattern of countTheftBldg, Poisson regression will be used in the predictive model.

ggplot(final_net, aes(countTheftBldg18)) +

  labs(title = "Distribution of Theft from Buildings by Grid Cell")

5.2 Cross-validated Poisson Regression

There are two sets of input data. One includes spatial structure of significant areas and the other doesnt. Two cross-validations methods are conducted. The first type seperates the dataset into 100 folds, and each fold is tested when the rest of the data are trained. The second cross- validation is based on the name of neighborhood: each neighborhood of data is tested when the rest of the data are trained.

final_net <-
  final_net %>%
  mutate(theftBldg18.isSig = 
           ifelse(local_morans[,5] <=0.0000001, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(theftBldg18.isSig.dist =
           nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)),
                       st_c(st_coid(
                         filter(final_net, theftBldg18.isSig == 1))), 1))

reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Garbage_Carts.nn", "Graffiti.nn", "Liquor_Retail.nn",
              "Police_Stations.nn", "Pot_Holes.nn", "Rodent_Baiting.nn", "Sanitation_Complaints.nn",
              "Street_Lights_All_Out.nn", "Tobacco_Retail.nn", "Tree_Debris.nn", "Tree_Trim.nn", 
              "loopDistance")

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Garbage_Carts.nn", "Graffiti.nn", "Liquor_Retail.nn",
              "Police_Stations.nn", "Pot_Holes.nn", "Rodent_Baiting.nn", "Sanitation_Complaints.nn",
              "Street_Lights_All_Out.nn", "Tobacco_Retail.nn", "Tree_Debris.nn", "Tree_Trim.nn", 
              "loopDistance", "theftBldg18.isSig", "theftBldg18.isSig.dist")

crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {
  
  allPredictions <- data.frame()
  cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])
  
  for (i in cvID_list) {
    
    thisFold <- i
    cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")
    
    fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
    fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
    
    regression <-
      glm(countTheftBldg18 ~ ., family = "poisson", 
          data = fold.train %>% 
            dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
    
    thisPrediction <- 
      mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
    allPredictions <-
      rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}  

reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countTheftBldg18",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countTheftBldg18, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countTheftBldg18",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countTheftBldg18, Prediction, geometry)

reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countTheftBldg18",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countTheftBldg18, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countTheftBldg18",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countTheftBldg18, Prediction, geometry)

reg.summary <-
  rbind(
  mutate(reg.cv, 
         Error = Prediction - countTheftBldg18, 
         Regression = "Randon k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
    mutate(reg.ss.cv,

  ) %>% 
  st_sf()

5.5 Generalizability Test

In generalizability test, we split the urban block groups into majority non-white areas and majority-white areas based on the dominate race in each block group. The result is interesting. The model with only risk factors overpredict majority non-white areas and underpredict majority areas, while the model including spatial process demonstrates an opposite answer. One potential explanation is the spatial overlaps of majority white block groups and hotspot of theft crimes.

6. Compare with Kernel Density

Global search radius is a key parameter when computing kernel density, which means the result of a kernel density map is majority based on the theory of autocorrelation. On the contrary, the risk prediction model involves several risk factors and result varies due to the feature selection. Consequently, the a risk predictions demonstrate more specific details and varieties in a result map.

7. Conclusion

Although the result of prediction model demonstrate relatively good accuracy with k-fold cross validation(MAE=0.56), I would not recommend this algorithm put into production for two flaws. First is the potential bias. At the beginning of the report, the potential bias in the reported theft from buildings has been discussed. One of the target of risk prediction model is to predict unreported crimes with risk factors. Since the hotspot of our prediction result is high consistent with the observed data, it is possible that some unseen thefts are not predicted by the selected features. In next steps, more risk factors and engineering methods should be test to optimize the capability of predict unreported crimes.

Besides, generalizability issues wait to be resolved. The prediction model is not generalizable enough in two aspects. First, based on the summary table, the prediction model overpredicts the count of theft in coolspot areas and underpredicts the number in hotspots. If the model is put into production, over-policing may happen in some urban blocks and cause uneven distribution. Second, the model with only risk factors overpredicts majority non-white areas and underpredicts majority areas, while the model including spatial process demonstrates an opposite answer. It would severely harm the social equity, if the racial discrepancy is not eliminated.
